Horace begins this ode with a second invocation to the Muses and a renewed pledge of his loyalty and devotion to thern. It was they who gave him safe escape at Philippi, protected him from the falling tree, and rescued him from drowning. Under their guardianship he may - wander all unharmed among savage tribes on the very outskirts of the world (1-36). It is also they who protect mighty Caesar and aid him with gentle counsel (37—42). At this point in the ode Horace turns with apparent abruptness to the story of the giants' defeat in their battle with the gods, and closes with a warning against dependence on brute force and violence (42-80). No Roman. however, would fail to see that Horace wished to present Augustus here as the vice-regent of} Α Jove, and that the powers of violence are those of rebellion against the· emperor's moderate and beneficent rule. In the next ode the compari- son is more outspoken.
